bout 1181","Europe":"Europe","France":"France","Montfort-sur-Meu, Rennes, Ille-et-Vilaine, Bretagne, France":"Montfort-sur-Meu, Ille-et-Vilaine, Brittany, France","Bretagne, France":"Brittany, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Gaël","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Americanized form of Polish   Gawel  . This form of the surname is also found in Slovakia, Czechia, and Germany.","French: metonymic occupational name for a harvester, from <i>javelle</i>, a term for a sheaf of grain which was loosely bound and left on the ground to ripen."],"variants":[{"name":"Gawel","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Janusz, Franciszek, Halina, Jolanta, Lucyna, Ludwik, Tadeusz, Wladyslaw, Zbigniew.","Polish and in some cases probably also Sorbian (<b>Gaweł</b>): from the personal name <i>Gaweł</i>, derived from Latin <i>Gallus</i> (see   Gall   3), the name borne by a 7th-century Irish missionary who was very active in central Europe. The extra syllable was introduced by analogy with Latin <i>Paulus</i>, which yielded Polish and (old) Sorbian <i>Paweł</i>. Compare   Gavel   and Czech   Havel  ."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Montfort","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French and Breton: variant of   Monfort   1. This surname is most common in Brittany and Haute-Savoie. See also 2 below.","Altered form of Dutch <b>Montfoort</b>: habitational name from Montfoort in Utrecht. It is a cognate of 1 above (see   Monfort   1) and also its altered form (or perhaps vice versa).","English (of Norman origin): very rare variant of   Mountford  , a cognate of 1 above."],"variants":[{"name":"Monfort","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French/Haitian Jacques, Marcel, Monique, Wilner.","French and Breton: habitational name from any of numerous places called Montfort, from Old French <i>mont</i> ‘hill’ (see   Mont   1) + <i>fort</i> ‘strong, impregnable’ (from Latin <i>fortis</i>). This surname is by far most common in Brittany. It is also found in Haiti. Compare   Montfort   1, see also 2 below.","Altered form of Dutch <b>Montfoort</b>, a variant of   Montfort   2 and also a cognate of the French name in 1 above and an altered form of its variant   Montfort   1 (or perhaps vice versa)."]},{"name":"Monforte","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Salvatore, Carmela, Carmine, Rocco, Rosaria, Sal.  Spanish Carlos, Francisco, Luis, Medardo.","Italian and Spanish: habitational name from any of numerous places called Monforte, from Latin <i>mons</i> ‘mountain’ (genitive <i>montis</i>) + <i>fortis</i> ‘strong’, probably a reference to the strategic position of these locations.","English (of Norman origin): variant of   Montfort  . This form of the surname is rare in Britain."]}]},{"name":"Guillaume","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Germanic.  See  <b>William</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"William","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Guillaume Gaël de Montfort was born about 1181, in Montfort-sur-Meu, Ille-et-Vilaine, Brittany, France, his father, Geoffroy I de Montfort-le-Hédé, was 37 and his mother, Gervaise de Saye, was 30. He married Nina de Rostrenen about 1212, in Europe. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 2 daughters. He died in France."},"et":{"Abt 1181–":"umbes 1181–Surnud","1175–1238":"1175–1238","1180–Male":"1180–Surnud","1180–Female":"1180–Surnud","1181–Male":"1181–Surnud","1185–Female":"1185–Surnud","1152–Female":"1152–Surnud","1214–1279":"1214–1279","1220–Male":"1220–Surnud","1230–Male":"1230–Surnud","–1263":"–1263","1145–1187":"1145–1187","1152–1205":"1152–1205","1187":"1187","1220":"1220","1230":"1230","1263":"1263","1175":"1175","Abt 1214":"umbes 1214","1152":"1152","1185":"1185","1181":"1181","1180":"1180","1205":"1205","1238":"1238","1214":"1214","1279":"1279","1168":"1168","1145":"1145","about 1212":"umbes 1212","about 1220":"umbes 1220","Abt 1181":"umbes 1181","Europe":"Europe","France":"Prantsusmaa","Montfort-sur-Meu, Rennes, Ille-et-Vilaine, Bretagne, France":"Montfort-sur-Meu, Ille-et-Vilaine, Bretagne, Prantsusmaa","Bretagne, France":"Bretagne, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"Abt 1181–":"noin 1181–Kuollut","1175–1238":"1175–1238","1180–Male":"1180–Kuollut","1180–Female":"1180–Kuollut","1181–Male":"1181–Kuollut","1185–Female":"1185–Kuollut","1152–Female":"1152–Kuollut","1214–1279":"1214–1279","1220–Male":"1220–Kuollut","1230–Male":"1230–Kuollut","–1263":"–1263","1145–1187":"1145–1187","1152–1205":"1152–1205","1187":"1187","1220":"1220","1230":"1230","1263":"1263","